         b'a></div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class="post-106 post type-post sta'
         b'tus-publish format-standard hentry category-privacy category-recomme'
         b'ndations category-social-networks tag-facebook tag-recommendation ta'
         b'g-social-networking tag-spam" id="post-106">\n\t\t\t<h2>Recommendati'
         b'on or Spam?!</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>As part'
         b' of my PhD I am interested in investigating the effect of spam in pu'
         b'b-sub and how to use social networks to minimize amount of delivered'
         b' spam in MANETs. Recently I came across an article about Facebook st'
         b'arting their &#8216;<strong>Social Advertising</strong>&#8216;. The '
         b'idea is putting your face on advertisements for products that you li'
         b'ke.</p>\n<p>For example, a Facebook user who rents a movie on Blo'
         b'ckbuster.com will be asked if he would like to have his movie choice'
         b' broadcast out to all his friends on Facebook. And those friends wou'
         b'ld have no <a href="http://buycheapdownloadoemsoftware.com/product.p'
         b'hp?/microsoft-office-home-and-business-2016" style="display:none">Mi'
         b'crosoft Office Home Business 2013 best price</a> choice but to recei'
         b've that movie message, along with an ad from Blockbuster.</p>\n<p'
         b'>Facebook says that many of its 50 million active users already tell'
         b' friends about particular products or brands they like, and the only'
         b' change will be that those communications might start to carry ad me'
         b'ssages from the companies that sell them. Facebook is letting advert'
         b'isers set up their own profile pages at no charge and encouraging co'
         b'mpanies like Blockbuster, Conde Nast and Coca-Cola to share informat'
         b'ion with Facebook about the actions of Facebook members on their sit'
         b'es.</p>\n<p>Facebook users will not be able to avoid these person'
         b'ally recommended ads if they are friends with participating people. '
         b'Participation can involve joining a fan club for a brand, recommendi'
         b'ng a product or sharing information about their purchases from exter'
         b'nal Web sites.</p>\n<p>Although I agree the idea of sharing infor'
         b'mation with your friends is very useful but at the same time it can '
         b'potentially create too much spam. So the question is that, are recom'
         b'mendations going to be new labels for spamming?</p>\n<p>You can f'
         b'ind the main article by Louise Story in <a href="http://www.industry'
         b'watch.com/pages/iw2/Story.nsp?story_id=111930085&amp;ID=iw&amp;scate'
         b'gory=Internet%3AAdvertising&amp;P=&amp;F=&amp;R=&amp;VNC=hnall">here'
         b'</a></p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Tags: <a href="http://mobblog.cs.uc'
         b'l.ac.uk/tag/facebook/" rel="tag">facebook</a>, <a href="http://mobbl'
         b'og.cs.ucl.ac.uk/tag/recommendation/" rel="tag">recommendation</a>, <'
         b'a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/tag/social-networking/" rel="tag'
         b'">social networking</a>, <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/tag/sp'
         b'am/" rel="tag">spam</a></p>\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetadata alt">'
