         b'class="says">says:</span>\t\t</div>\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class="comment-m'
         b'eta commentmetadata"><a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/11/22'
         b'/recommendation-or-spam/#comment-1316">\n\t\t\tNovember 23, 2007 at '
         b'2:41 pm</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<p>Hi there,</p>\n<p>I am also doing m'
         b'y phd in preventing potentially unwanted messages from being deliver'
         b'ed. I also believe that spam is highly subjective.</p>\n<p>My app'
         b'roach is a bit different from the one in the article quoted about Br'
         b'itney. Messages can be delivered to any friend-of-a-friend, as long '
         b'as all of the friends in the path are willing to forward the message'
         b'. The message recipient can complain about the message if it deems i'
         b't to be spam. All the friends which forwarded the message are inform'
         b'ed about the complain so that they can do a better job at forwarding'
         b' messages in the future, by filtering the messages from senders whic'
         b'h receive many complaints.</p>\n<p>As you can see the whole point'
         b' here is that you do not want to make direct connections to anyone f'
         b'ast, because then there are no intermediate friends that could filte'
         b'r spam messages from them. I am still working on a complete model of'
         b' the social network. But if you want to see the work that led to thi'
         b's idea, you can check my website.</p>\n\n\t\t<div class="reply">'
         b'\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n'
